The divi- sions of the speech enumerated above are also very nearly identical with those given by Cic. 1. c. I 41, 185 ff. in advocacy of the study of civil law.—ipse securus=cum sis securus. This use of an adjective (or substantive) for a subordinate clause is one of the most characteristic features of the style of Tacitus. Cf. c. 1 13 iuvenis (cum i. essem) 7 2 homo novus (quamquam) 8 16 egregius 27 4 mitior. In Ag. (12 exx.) G. (6) Hist. (121) Ann. (183). The combination of this elliptical construction and a subordinate clause is first met with in Ag. 39, curis exercitus quodque—statuit and thereafter with inci-easing frequency. Cp. Ihm, Quae-st. Sym. p. 5 ff. where examples from other writers, especially Caesar and Horace (e. g. Sat. I 1, 35 II 1, 16) are also cited. For a somewhat analogous brachylogy, cf. Nipp. Ann.
